Over the past few years, Case-Based Reasoning (CBR) has grown from a Yalecentric view of cognition to a solid sub-area that is supported by wide-spread academic research and industrial development. Unfortunately, the definition of what is and is not CBR remains seriously ambiguous. In this talk, I will look at different takes on CBR and suggest a definition that, oddly enough, doesn’t include the use of “cases ” . In particular I will look at: